1. Calculate the circumference of the original circle:

\[
C = 2 \pi \times 4 = 8 \pi \, \text{inches}
\]

2. Calculate the arc length of the sector that forms the cone:

\[
\text{Arc Length} = \frac{3}{4} \times 8 \pi = 6 \pi \, \text{inches}
\]

This arc length becomes the circumference of the base of the cone.

3. Thus, the circumference of the base of the resulting cone is:

\[
\boxed{6 \pi}
\]
We solved the problem step-by-step using reasoning to show that the circumference of the base of the resulting cone is \(6\pi\).

